text:
The Old Custom House on Wall Street, South side occupies a Square bounded by Wall, William Hanover and Exchange Place. It is built of Quincy granite and originally was called the Merchants Exchange.

Urbrock Collection.

1870.
title: Manhattan: Wall Street

text:
Wall Street, north side, west from William Street (right), across Nassau Street (center), to Broadway (left margin). Shown is an early view of the financial district. The date of the view is determined by the absence of the Washington statue on the Sub Treasury steps (1883) and the presence of the massive National Bank of the Republic (1886) to the right of Trinity Church.

Between 1880-3

Gift of Urbrock Collection

NOTE: To the right of the sub-treasury Bldg is the old U.S. Branch Bank, late the U.S. Assay Office.
On the extreme right of the view is the Merchant's National Bank.

Wall Street, at the N.W. corner of William Street. About 1885
Gift of E.M. Jenks
Note: This is the old Bank of America Bldg.

Wall Street, west from William Street (foreground), to Broadway, showing on the west side of the latter, at the head of this thoroughfare, Trinity Church. This early view of the financial district is conspicious by the absence of the following institutions: The U. S. Trust Company of New York building of 1888 (No. 45-47); The heightened U. S. National Bank of New York building of 1890 (No. 41); The third (9 story) building of the Mechanics National Bank (No. 31-33); The Wilks Building at the
S.W. corner of Wall and Broad Streets; The Gallatin National Bank building of 1887 (in the process of construction at No. 34-36, adjoining the Assay Office) and the Bank of America building of 1888-9 (No. 44-6).

Compare this view with one of 1895 and note the changes; the last of that period to go was the brownstone shown at the left; the site to this day (1938) being occupied by the same firm, the Atlantic Mutual Insurance Company. An account of same was carried in a column titled
"Sky Lines' in the New York Sun of April 28, 1938.

Subsequently the following were replaced; the Drexel Morgan & Co. building in 1913; the old United States Assay Office building in 1916; and the Mechanics National Bank building in 1932. 1929 saw the site for the present 7O storied Bank of Manhattan Building (No. 40) cleared.

No. 2 of this set shows a view slightly later; the Gallatin National Bank Building being completed and with a workmens scaffold about to be removed. This structure was erected on a site which included their former building and a 1ot purchased from the dissolved Union Bank which was adjacent. The purchase price for the latter was $400000. The new nine story building was built and owned jointly by the Bank and Adrian Iselin.

Wall Street, west from William Street, to Broadway, showing prominently the northerly side of this financial thoroughfare. Trinity Church, at the latter point dominates this locale. Preceding same to the right is the massive National Bank of the Republic (Fort Sherman). To the left of the telegraph pole in the foreground is the ornate Drexel Morgan S Co. Bldg. Opposite are the entablatured U.S. Sub Treasury and Assay Office buildings. Adjacent to the last is the partially completed Gallatin National Bank Bldg.
About 1887
Thru New York Historical Society

Wall Street, at the N.W. corner of William Street. Also shown is William Street, at and adjoining the N.W. corner of Wall Street. The building concerned is the Bank of America.

About 1890.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.

Wall Street, north side, west from (No. 50, building at right) a point to the east of William Street and across same to Broadway (left, Trinity Church seen on the north side of same). From (left) to right appear the Royal Insurance Building (No. 50); the Bank of New York (No. 48, building erected 1857); the Bank of America (No. 44-46, building erected 1888-1889); the Merchants National Bank (No. 40-42, erected 1884); a small 7 story structure, No. 38; the Gallatin National Bank (No. 36, erected 1887); the Assay office; the United States Sub treasury; the Gillenden Building; several others and finally the National Bank of the Republic (erected 1880).

About 1895.

Ewing Galloway

Wall Street, West, from but not including William Street, to Broadway. Showing Trinity Church in the backaround,
1896.
Ewing Galloway.

title: Wall Street - William Street looking northwest

text:
(1) Wall Street, west from William Street to Broadway and showing Trinity Church at that point. Note the changed aspects of this thoroughfare from an earlier view of 1890. (q.v.); buildings mentioned there in being here apparent. The prominent structure occupying the N.W. corner of Wall and Nassau Streets is the Gillenden Building which in 1911 will make way for the present (1938) Bankers Trust Company Building.

June 1, 1904.

Brown Brothers.

(2) A similar view emphasizing the south side of this thoroughfare. Note the Drexel, Morgan and the Wilks Buildings occupying opposite corners (S.E. and S.W. respectively) of this and Broad Street.

June 1906.

George L. Balgue.

Wall Street, south side, east from William (right) to Hanover (left) Streets, showing the National City Bank. This structure was originally the Merchants Exchange and later became the U. S. Custom House. It occupies an entire square, extending to Exchange Place.
About 1905
Gift of Urbrock Collection

William Street, south from but not including Wall Street.
About 1915.

Wall Street, north side, west from (No. 34-36, right), a point midway between William and Nassau Streets, across the latter to Broadway and showing in a progressive order, the Gallatin National Bank; the United States Assay Office; the United States Sub-Treasury; the Bankers Trust Co. (39-stories); the Astor Building and the First National Bank. The Gallatin Bank appearing on the right will be demolished in 1929 and its site will be included for the new 70-story Bank of Manhattan Building. Prior to that date the Assay Office was rebuilt to 4-stories.

1916.

Gift of Albert A. Volk Co.

Wall Street, south side, west from William to Broad Streets, showing respectively the 18-story Atlantic Building, No. 49-51; the 9-story U. S. Trust Co. Building, No. 45; the 25-story Equitable Trust Company Building, No. 37-43; a 10-story office structure and the 4-story J. P. Morgan and Company Building, No. 23-33. Across the latter appears the Wilks Building and a portion of the N. Y. Stock Exchange.

About 1922

Wall Street at the N.E. corner of William Street. On this site will be erected the new National City Building, No. 52 Wall Street.

August 29, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

48-52 Wall Street, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of William Street. The building bearing ornament is the Bank of New York Building, (No. 48) and is directly at the afore said corner. Preceding same, is the National City Building (No. 52) prominently shown on the left, is the Equitable Building (two units of 38-stories). The Woolworth Building appears on the right.

About 1928.

Brown Brothers.

Wall Street (center) at William Street (from left foreground to center), showing 4 corners of this intersection with building units at each. In the foreground is the National City Bank; to the left, the Atlantic Bldg.; in the center, the Bank of America (adjoining same is the 70 storied Bank of Manhattan Building under construction); and the Bank of New York. Between the latter two appears a glimpse of the Woolworth Tower. Note at the left, the pyramid atop the Bankers Trust Co. Bldg. and also the Equitable Building.
The photographer is viewing north westward from atop the Cotton Exchange at Hanover Square.

August 18, 1929.

P. L. Sperr

General View--Lower Manhattan, Financial District: Several views of the Wall Street skyscraper area, showing (view 1) the site of the 70-story Bank of Manhattan Building at Wall and William Streets. The old buildings are shown being razed.

View 2 shows the completed Bank of Manhattan tower in the center, the International Telephone Building on the left and the City Bank Farmers Trust Building under construction.

View 4 shows the Bank of Manhattan tower seen across the pyramidal tower of the Bankers Trust Building. On the left is the Equitable Building.

P. L. Sperr 1-3

View 2: August 6, 1930
View 3: December 1, 1932

text:
Wall Street, east from William Street to the East River. Note the subway station at the N.E. corner of this intersection and the South Ferry division of the Second and Third Aves. Elevated Lines on Pearl Street. The dark wall on the right is the northern side of the National City Bank.

November 7, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

70 Pine Street, (Sixty Wall Tower): west side, of Pearl Street from Pine to Cedar Streets showing a panoramic view northward).

View No. 1 is westward towards the North (Hudson) River and overlooking the Singer, New York Telephone, Transportation and Woolworth Buildings. Note the Queen Mary "outward bound."

View No. 2 is due north towards the 42nd Street-Midtown zone. In the foreground here are the Municipal Building, the Federal Courts Building, and other civic structures.

View No. 3 is eastward towards the East River and overlooks the lower East Side. The bridges shown in a respective order are, the Brooklyn, the Manhattan and the Williamsburg. Note between the first two mentioned, the white building pile constituting Knickerbocker Village. The marginal thoroughfare is South Street which terminates in the distance at Corlears Hook.

September 8, 1937
Views: 1-2-3

P. L. Sperr
